Bank Churn Prediction

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

Businesses like banks which provide service have to worry about problem of 'Customer Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Objective¶

You as a Data scientist with the bank need to build a neural network based classifier that can determine whether a customer will leave the bank or not in the next 6 months.

Data Dictionary¶

  • CustomerId: Unique ID which is assigned to each customer

  • Surname: Last name of the customer

  • CreditScore: It defines the credit history of the customer.

  • Geography: A customer’s location

  • Gender: It defines the Gender of the customer

  • Age: Age of the customer

  • Tenure: Number of years for which the customer has been with the bank

  • NumOfProducts: refers to the number of products that a customer has purchased through the bank.

  • Balance: Account balance

  • HasCrCard: It is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer has credit card or not.

  • EstimatedSalary: Estimated salary

  • isActiveMember: Is is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer is active member of the bank or not ( Active member in the sense, using bank products regularly, making transactions etc )

  • Exited : whether or not the customer left the bank within six month. It can take two values ** 0=No ( Customer did not leave the bank ) ** 1=Yes ( Customer left the bank )

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# function to plot stacked bar chart

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()
In [16]:
### Function to plot distributions

def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Data Preprocessing¶






















During our univariate analysis we saw outliers mainly in two attributes: Age and CreditScore. Let's us briefly discuss our course of action regarding these.


    

  • Age: The outliers here are mainly due to the clients with an extreme old age. This could be due to the natural age of customers or a customer who has not updated its status. Nevertheless, we will keep this data as it is plausible data.
    • 

  • CreditScore: The outliers fall short of a score of 400. However, the number of these observations are very low. This might not impact the training model as it can be a plausible score or very low noise. We shall keep these values.
    • 



Note: This treatment is subjective to the scientist, so different courses of action may be taken with a different data scientist


After going through the data, we shall prepare the data to train the model. It is important to remember the prevention of data leakage into the model.






















Dummy Variable Creation¶






















Here, we will create dummy variables for our categorical attributes. Currently, our dataset has two different representation of categorical data:


    

  • Gender and Geography, which are represented by an alphanumerical value; and HasCrCard & IsActiveMember, which are represented by boolean values ("1" and "0").
    • 



We will create dummy variable for the former type of attributes. As for the latter, we will simply convert it to an uint8 type as it stores the same information (either 0 or 1) with less space in memory. Afterwards, we will separate our target variable into a separate variable, denoted as y.

Data Normalization¶






















In this section, we will Normalize the numerical data. This is mainly due to the difference in standard deviation between the columns, i.e. Balance and CreditScore.


However, it is important to note the order of this operation in regard to our previous step. By splitting the data into 3 sections, we ensure that the normalization is not affected by the separation and each set is independant of each other; thus preventing data leakage.


The downside of this is that we will have to repeat the operation for each dataset, however this operation is cheap in terms of computation so it is a simple task to execute.

Model Building¶






















Model Evaluation Criterion¶






















The nature of predictions made by the classification model has two different kinds of errors:


    

  • False negatives (FN) are customers that are not predicted to leave, but they have exited.
    • 

  • False positives (FP) are failure detections in the model where we predict a customer exiting where they actually stay with the bank.
    • 



Which metric to optimize?


Management currently wants to focus on the customers who have actually left and their reasonings. Therefore, we want to minimize the number of false negative as we want to identify correctly the customers who might leave rather than those who might stay.

To accomplish this, we will focus on the Recall metric, and increasing its value.


Note: This does not imply that we are disregarding the false positives. We are merely giving priority to reduce the error in False Negative. This also applies to our perception of the different metrics.






















Utility Functions¶






















Here we will define some utility functions needed throughout the rest of the notebook.


















In [31]:






def plot(history, name):
    """
    Function to plot loss/accuracy

    history: an object which stores the metrics and losses.
    name: can be one of Loss or Accuracy
    """
    fig, ax = plt.subplots() #Creating a subplot with figure and axes.
    plt.plot(history.history[name]) #Plotting the train accuracy or train loss
    plt.plot(history.history['val_'+name]) #Plotting the validation accuracy or validation loss

    plt.title('Model ' + name.capitalize()) #Defining the title of the plot.
    plt.ylabel(name.capitalize()) #Capitalizing the first letter.
    plt.xlabel('Epoch') #Defining the label for the x-axis.
    fig.legend(['Train', 'Validation'], loc="outside right upper") #Defining the legend, loc controls the position of the legend.





















In [32]:






# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using statsmodels
def model_performance_classification(
    model, predictors, target, threshold=0.5
):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    threshold: threshold for classifying the observation as class 1
    """

    # checking which probabilities are greater than threshold
    pred = model.predict(predictors) > threshold
    # pred_temp = model.predict(predictors) > threshold
    # # rounding off the above values to get classes
    # pred = np.round(pred_temp)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1 Score": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

























Neural Network with SGD Optimizer¶






















We will begin with building a dense neural network, consisting of the following:


    

  • 3 hidden layer with 32 neurons, 16 neurons, and 8 neurons respectively.
      

    • This number of neurons will mostly remained unchanged throughout the rest of the models. If its changed, it will be mentioned.
      • 

    

    • 

  • Activation funtion of ReLU
    • 

  • Scothastic Gradient Descent as the optimizer.
    • 

  • Initialize the weights with the He Initializer.
    • 



There are two main parameters that we will define here and apply equally to all the different NNs (Neural Network).


    

  • Epochs: This is the number of training samples processed together in a single forward and backward pass. We will define it as 32.
    • 

  • Batch: This is the number of training samples processed together in a single forward and backward pass. We will define it as 64.
    • 



These values can be changed to observe better or worse performances. However, for this particular case, we will not change their values as we will implement other methods to change performance.


Additionally, since earlier we saw an inbalance with our target class (as in more users have not exited, more 0 than 1), we will establish the class weights in a dictionary with the purpose of giving priority to the minority class.

# defining the batch size and # epochs upfront as we'll be using the same values for all models

# Calculate class weights for imbalanced dataset
cw = (y_train.shape[0]) / np.bincount(y_train)

# Create a dictionary mapping class indices to their respective class weights

    cw_dict[i] = cw[i]

Neural Network with Balanced Data (by applying SMOTE) and SGD Optimizer¶






















Now, we will create the same 3 models as before. However, the main thing we will change between all of the models is to apply oversampling techniques to the data. Specifically, SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique).


Here, we'll build the first model with SMOTE data. But first, we will apply the Over-sampling technique to be applied to the 3 remaining models.






















Oversampling the data¶


















In [56]:






# # Synthetic Minority Over Sampling Technique
sm = SMOTE(sampling_strategy=1, k_neighbors=5, random_state=0)
X_train_over, y_train_over = sm.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

# adding dropout layer

___Selection of the Final Model__


The final model to be chosen has to have high recall score mainly. However, one must not disregard the rest of the performance of the models. A model that had a high recall score but scored badly in precision (which is reflected by having a bad F1 score) it will not be considered a good model as it disregards a lot of data we would like it to consider. Another point to keep in mind is the drive for the model to overfit. We must choose a model that does not overfit and can operate well with unseen data. This is a struggle for most neural networks as their complexity compels them to overfit; for the business' interest we will choose one that keeps all this points in mind.


After considering the models' perfomances, as well after various runs (not reflected in this notebook) we will choose our 3rd model for our final model, i.e. the NN with Adam & Dropout.


    

  • The model had good recall score, and consistently the highest recall score.
    • 

  • Among the other models, it also had consistenly good F1 scores.
    • 

  • Both the training and validation scores are similar, and the differences are miniscule.
    • 



Note: The model chosen does not mean that a better model doesn't exist. A different algorithm, with different criteria established by a different data scientist may obtain similar or different models. The model chosen is simply a judgement from the models presented in this notebook.

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶






















    

  • Most of the customers are between the ages of 30 and 45; additionally, as one's age increases the more exited customers are observed. Specifically, the 75% range of customers who have exited vs those that haven't is shifted by 10 years. (In other words, the range of customers who exited is of [37-51] while those that stayed is of [30-40])
      

    • Other factors as for the exiting customers are: 6 months absence from their activity (IsActiveMember values decreasing as customers exit), and the balance in their account takes a small role in their decision.
      • 

    

    • 

  • Most customers have a balance of 0, however, for exited customers this large modality sees a proportional decrease (as in the percent of customers with 0 against those who have)
    • 

  • Most customers are from France, however Germany based customers have less customers with a balance of 0.
      

    • In regards to this last point, more customers from Germany have exited the bank.
      • 

    

    • 

  • The number of products most customers have is between 1-2, and people that have 3-4 products tend to have a shorter range of balance (as in people that buy 3-4 products do not have extreme values of balance)
      

    • Most people that has bought 3-4 products have exited the bank.
      • 

    

    • 

  • In order to see better performance of the model, more features may be needed. Additionally, more observations will help improve the model's performance and development.
